</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/1232677-larisa"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1440409876i/1232677._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/1232677-larisa">Larisa</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    All of these phrases are from famous historical figures from Ovid to Newton. "Precibus infimis," for example, is from Livy, meaning, "with ineffective<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    All of these phrases are from famous historical figures from Ovid to Newton. "Precibus infimis," for example, is from Livy, meaning, "with ineffective prayers". I have finished the book now and so can't easily locate all of the Latin, but the final Latin phrase, "hypotheses non fingo," means, "I do not feign hypotheses," and was one of Newton's additions to the 2nd edition of his Principia. It was one of Newton's few comments on his own method and one that has been subject to a lot of controversy because one might ask why Newton as a scientist would object to the use of hypotheses. I could go on about the meaning of this quote and what I take to be its significance in Erasure, but I think I should probably leave off here. I hope this helps!<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

