    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_459835363" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/459835363" />
    <a title="Aubrey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4119460-aubrey"><img alt="Aubrey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1472535045p2/4119460.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/459835363?book_show_action=true">Jul 15, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aubrey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aubrey" href="/user/show/4119460-aubrey">Aubrey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781584650904" href="/book/show/1663955.Erasure">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=person-of-everything">person-of-everything</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=1-read-on-hand">1-read-on-hand</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=antidote-think-twice-read">antidote-think-twice-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=4-star">4-star</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=r-goodreads">r-goodreads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=antidote-think-twice-all">antidote-think-twice-all</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=r-2019">r-2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=21st-c-proposed">21st-c-proposed</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer459835363" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer948097807216868644"><blockquote>
  <i>There was an incredibly dense novel from a well-known, reclusive writer of dense novels. There was a nicely crafted and notably lean novel from a writer whose reputation was astonishingly well made. There was a volume of collected stories from a dead writer, a shelf of first novels about fatherly abuse and motherly alcoholism (and the reverse), a mid-list author&apos;s new (but dreadfully old) take on the academic novel, twenty-eight middle America, domestic, where-will-the-children-live novels, f</i></blockquote></span>
  <span id="freeText948097807216868644" style="display:none"><blockquote>
  <i>There was an incredibly dense novel from a well-known, reclusive writer of dense novels. There was a nicely crafted and notably lean novel from a writer whose reputation was astonishingly well made. There was a volume of collected stories from a dead writer, a shelf of first novels about fatherly abuse and motherly alcoholism (and the reverse), a mid-list author's new (but dreadfully old) take on the academic novel, twenty-eight middle America, domestic, where-will-the-children-live novels, forty coming-of-age novels, thirty-five new-life-after-the-wrecked-marriage novels, thirty crime novels, forty so-called adventure novels and six yeah-we're-Christians-with-chips-on-our-shoulders novels. For the most part the titles received more consideration than the stories or the writing.</i>
</blockquote>This'll have been the 123rd (now the 124th with my recent finishing of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/113404.Home_and_Exile" title="Home and Exile by Chinua Achebe" rel="nofollow noopener">Home and Exile</a>) book that I've read that was written by a black person. This is not a number that indicates any sort of linear distance from instigated goal setting to penultimate finishing, although I must mention that before coming onto GR, I had read three, maybe four books of the author demographic: some obfuscated by the white status quo such as Dumas, others assigned in school. Whatever concrete meaning can be drawn from the number is embodied by the fact that Everett's text did not disturb or shame me as much as I honestly feared it would, although I do plan as a result of this to reread <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15622.Native_Son" title="Native Son by Richard Wright" rel="nofollow noopener">Native Son</a> at some point and see what has changed and what has not. Another side effect of this number is that I have largely run through most of the mainstream tomes (with some such as <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/765172.Cane" title="Cane by Jean Toomer" rel="nofollow noopener">Cane</a> waiting in the possible wings), and so I find myself more and more in the experimental, the poetical, the translated, Oyeyemi and Walcott and Vera, for better or worse. I would love to sit down with Everett and compare reading notes, but we're both busy people, and he probably doesn't need to deal with another white chick fumbling at the black canon and hoping on the inside will praise her for it.<blockquote>
  <i>If you didn't like Clancy's white people, you could go out and read about some others.</i>
</blockquote>This book is scathing, amusing, and terrifying in certain key ways, especially if you dwell as much as I do on how US literature barely functions under capitalism, seeing as how freedom of speech has never guaranteed your freedom to not starve to death on the street. Every so often an unburied wunderkind crops up, but that's just the convenience of being able to more effectively capitalize off of death bodies can neither agree or disagree on how their particular soul is sold. 'Erasure's' main character, for all the academic suburbanity, is inextricably fixed in one of the more vulnerable points of society as evidence by the violence, stigma, and lack of promotion that slowly but surely builds up to a rock and hard place that devolves into the inevitability that is the book's conclusion. Some reviewers argue that some of the white people presented in the book are stereotypes: I honestly have to wonder whether these reviewers are as aggressively astute with the rest of their reading. Anyways, I'd say that this work is a vital piece of satire for the 21st century arena of US literature both "high" and "low", and it's hard to tell whether the eight years of Obama have really changed much in terms of who becomes a bestseller and, more importantly, who must first assume "the mantel of their people" before being afforded economic security. Pertinent questions so long as the free market reigns supreme and the arts continue to be choked out by mechanical cogs in a techno-industrial complex. Finally, if you as a reader are in any way pissed off at this book, your work is laid out of you, and you should honestly be thanking Everett for pointing out for such.<br /><br />I've got another of Everett's works on the digital docket, although I haven't acquired a copy yet. He's definitely one of the authors who are doing more interesting things these days, and the self-awareness in some of the places from the Man-Booker-level-prize-hype to modern market spewing out talk show features and movies faster than one can take a breath is so incisive it hurts. If every author had as much critical thinking skills and sense of social responsibility as Everett does, we'd definitely get less books published every year, as when you perceive the Void for what it is, it's that much less likely to spit a six figure contract back at you. On the other hand, who am I to gate-keep an already horrendously gatekept profession in a manner that does little more than brownnose the existing status quo, save with something a little more "liberal" and a lot more censorship with a different hat. Honestly, in light of this, I have to keep giving "contemporary" (post-2000 for me) lit a chance, as every so often it throws my own thoughts back at me and shows me that I'm not the only one pondering the absolute mess of calcification of the literature market: half pandering power play, half token minority, all "progress" that will accomplish nothing by the time the last glacier melts to drowning. What does the future hold? Depends on all the people who think they can substitute paychecks for paying attention.<blockquote>
  <i>I promised myself once that I would not compromise my art.</i>
</blockquote></span>
  <a data-text-id="948097807216868644" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


