    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2326966588" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2326966588" />
    <a title="Nichole" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7728901-nichole"><img alt="Nichole" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1507428125p2/7728901.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2326966588?book_show_action=true">Mar 13, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nichole" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nichole" href="/user/show/7728901-nichole">Nichole</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19492105-erasure">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7728901-nichole?shelf=african-diaspora">african-diaspora</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7728901-nichole?shelf=books-about-books">books-about-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7728901-nichole?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2326966588" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14458591000928399886">I just finished reading this funny and smart book a few days ago. Because it was published in 2001 (I am late to the party, as usual), I will not give a rundown of the story; it&apos;s been done so many times already. I cannot add anything new. Booklist did it right:<br/><br/>From Booklist:<br/><br/>&quot;Thelonius &quot;Monk&quot; Ellison, author of experimental novels, is somewhat estranged from his family because he was favored by an emotionally distant, recently deceased father. When his sister is killed, Monk returns to Washingto</span>
  <span id="freeText14458591000928399886" style="display:none">I just finished reading this funny and smart book a few days ago. Because it was published in 2001 (I am late to the party, as usual), I will not give a rundown of the story; it's been done so many times already. I cannot add anything new. Booklist did it right:<br /><br />From Booklist:<br /><br />"Thelonius "Monk" Ellison, author of experimental novels, is somewhat estranged from his family because he was favored by an emotionally distant, recently deceased father. When his sister is killed, Monk returns to Washington, D.C., to care for his mother, who is in the early stages of Alzheimer's disease. At the same time that he deals with family crises, Monk is also in the midst of a professional crisis after the seventh rejection of his most recent novel. In a fury over the success of We's Lives in Da Ghetto, a debut novel by a black woman exploiting racial stereotypes, Monk writes his own ultra ghetto novel. It is a parody, reminiscent of Native Son but with none of the pathos and perspective. Monk's main character is an Ebonics-spouting brute with no regard for his four children or their respective mothers. To his chagrin, the novel is a success, and Monk is left to struggle with artistic ethics versus the comforts of wealth.<br /><br />Little things I liked about the book:<br /><br />1. The protagonist - Thelonius "Monk" Ellison is an writer of rejected avant-garde books. He is a reluctant scion of the elite. He comes from a cold family. He never feels "black" enough. He is an intellectual. I love it.<br /><br />2. French Criticism - Monk specializes in French new criticism theory. At a literary debate, he presents a dense, hard-to-understand French-style deconstruction of a famous novel. Nobody understands it, and it soon leads to a awkward fistfight between Monk and another professor.<br /><br />3. "My Pafology" - This book-within-a-book was genius. Using a pen name, Monk scribbled this hilarious little "ghetto-lit" book out of a sense of desperation (he had to care for his dying mother). "My Pafology" will make him rich. And depressed.<br /><br />4. Erasure is similar in a lot of ways to <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/36325106.The_Emperor_of_Ocean_Park" title="The Emperor of Ocean Park by Stephen L. Carter" rel="nofollow noopener">The Emperor of Ocean Park</a> in terms of character types (dissatisfied black professionals), settings (black Washington, D. C., Annapolis, Martha's Vineyard), atmosphere, and even language. I really enjoyed that.<br /><br />That is all. I really liked the book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14458591000928399886" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


