<div id="review_2504024177" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2504024177" />
    <a title="Andrew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/442654-andrew"><img alt="Andrew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1513093267p2/442654.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2504024177?book_show_action=true">Aug 22, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andrew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andrew" href="/user/show/442654-andrew">Andrew</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/442654-andrew?shelf=2000s-american-fiction">2000s-american-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/442654-andrew?shelf=american-fiction">american-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2504024177" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16213887641540071025">I read Erasure thinking of every black friend I&apos;ve had whose white acquaintances have asked them to recommend some hip-hop out of the blue, every black man I know who gets approached at the club by white women trying to mime black cadences so she can live out her stallion fantasy, every black woman I know whose co-workers tell her how pretty her hair is, and is that an African style in origin? I read Erasure thinking of every black friend, classmate, colleague, and neighbor I have who at the end</span>
  <span id="freeText16213887641540071025" style="display:none">I read Erasure thinking of every black friend I've had whose white acquaintances have asked them to recommend some hip-hop out of the blue, every black man I know who gets approached at the club by white women trying to mime black cadences so she can live out her stallion fantasy, every black woman I know whose co-workers tell her how pretty her hair is, and is that an African style in origin? I read Erasure thinking of every black friend, classmate, colleague, and neighbor I have who at the end of the day was just expected to act like an updated version of a plantation darkie. And I read Erasure thinking of my own past, where I've been guilty of fetishizing black culture in that very innocent-eyed Midwestern way, where I've been guilty of asking black friends questions as if they were a proxy for their people as a whole -- after all, as a child in my little town, the closest thing I had to black friends were Arnold and Willis from Diff'rent Strokes.<br /><br />Erasure is like Pale Fire, except instead of a shitty narrative poem we have something designed to resemble Precious... or rather, it winds up being the Don’t Be a Menace version of Precious (and yes I know the novel is called Push, but the movie version is what resonates these days). A writer gives his final fuck-you, and Percival Everett delivers his poisoned valentine to the publishing industry.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16213887641540071025" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


